english:
  title: Continuation of the Duryu Record
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A scholar born into one place is bound like a gourd or melon to his corner of earth—such is fate. Unable to traverse all under Heaven to gather knowledge for the future, one must at least explore the mountains and streams of one's own realm. Yet human affairs are riddled with contradiction, and nine times in ten, desire yields to disappointment.

    I first sought office as a scholar in Jinju, hoping for peace to nurture my mother. Yet even Ge Zhichuan, the governor of Goulou, could not abandon his pursuit of cinnabar. Duryu Mountain lies within Jinju's borders. Upon arrival, I prepared myself daily for climbing, for the mists and cranes of Duryu were to be my cinnabar. Two years on the magistrate's bench brought only mockery of a swollen belly. I feigned illness and retired, yearning for wandering—yet my feet never once touched Duryu's paths. How could such original purpose remain unfulfilled?

    Still, I never forgot Duryu Mountain. Often I and Master Cao Taoxu planned journeys together, but he was bound by office and I by circumstance. Soon Taoxu departed to Tianling, bearing mourning. Jin Baiyuan, a gentleman scholar of Tianling, was my spiritual friend. This spring, when singing the Deer Cry in Daozhou, he passed my gate and proposed visiting Duryu. Then Minister Kim came south to inspect Lingnan, his letters repeatedly urging a meeting I could not keep. On the eleventh day of the fourth month, I sought him out at Tianling. Learning that Baiyuan had left for the capital five days prior, we met instead. The Minister offered to take me with him, but I declined, bound by mountain promises. He pressed gifts upon me, lamenting that court duties and failing health prevented my company.

    Li Zian, the new magistrate of Tianling, was my former teacher at the National Academy and generous with provisions. Lin Zhenshu of Tianling agreed to join us. On the fourteenth day, we departed Tianling's south gate, traveling west some twenty li to a stream and a small inn called Tixian. From there, ascending and descending ridges for ten li, we entered a beautiful landscape where two mountains faced each other and a spring flowed between them.

    Climbing a ridge, my attendants said I must dismount and pay respects. To whom? "Heaven King," they answered. Not knowing what this Heaven King might be, I spurred my horse onward. Rain fell like torrents that day, mist clung to the mountains, and my attendants, dressed in rain gear, became separated. My horse found its way to Denggui Temple, so named because the mountain's form resembles a turtle and the temple sits upon its back. Ancient walls rose steeply; crevices held dark caves where mountain water rushed, gurgling. To the east and west stood two halls. We lodged in the eastern one, sent attendants home, and remained as rain persisted through night and day.

    Suddenly the rain cleared. Three blue peaks rose before our door, white clouds drifted across them, emerald shadows played upon the stone. I jested, "Does the Creator take an interest in such things? Does it hide the mountain in jealousy of us?" Baiyuan replied, "Perhaps the mountain spirit has long detained us poets for its own purposes."

    The night cleared further. Moonlight flooded the landscape. Craggy peaks and deep valleys seemed alive with immortals dancing. "The human heart at night knows no impurity," Baiyuan said. I had my young servant, who played the bamboo pipe well, sound it forth. The three of us sat in silence as midnight came.

    At dawn, Baiyuan and I put on straw sandals and took up walking staves, descending Denggui for about a li to find a waterfall. After ten li more through a sparse village of persimmon trees, climbing around hillsides, we came to a spring beneath rocks. Drinking our fill, we proceeded another li to Jintai Hermitage.

    A monk came out drawing water. Without ceremony, we entered. Peonies bloomed in the courtyard, half-withered but still vivid red. Some twenty or more monks in patched robes were chanting sutras, processing rapidly. I asked what this was. "A Diligent Practice Sanctuary," explained Baiyuan. "The practice is pure without mixture, advancing without retreat, unceasing day and night. Should anyone drowse, an agile monk strikes a wooden board to keep them awake." "Monkhood is arduous indeed," I observed. "Yet if scholars pursued sainthood with such discipline, would they not surely achieve it?"

    The hermitage housed an ancient six-ringed staff. By noon we returned, looking down at the stream swollen like a lake. We could see the Shangjuwuzhu Temple in the distance but could not cross. The mountain path descended steeply. I planted my staff and slid downward. My horse waited below, and when I mounted, it limped on one leg like a mortar and pestle. "Even lame donkeys have their place in poetry," I remarked to Baiyuan.

    Following the stream's north bank eastward, we reached Longyou Pool, where the landscape north and south was profound and marvelous. Zhenshu waited for us on the rocks with provisions. The water was high; we could not see the pool's true form. "This is where Administrator Zhanbi fasted and prayed for rain," Zhenshu said. The pool stones resembled plowed fields with many traces. Some rocks formed vessels like urns and cauldrons. People believed these were dragon's utensils. "Not at all," I said. "Torrential streams wear stone smooth with time. How foolish are common folk to prefer such tales to reason."

    From the pool eastward, the path grew treacherous, dropping a thousand feet. We proceeded in terror for nearly thirty li. Across the valley, we glimpsed Duryu's eastern slopes—ancient vines and old trees obscured countless temple pavilions. Yet a weak river separated us, impassable as the Weishui. The terrain gradually flattened; ahead rose three peaks from the north. Below stood barely a dozen houses—the village of Coal Mountain. "This could be habitable," Baiyuan suggested. "The Literary Brush Peak ahead is even finer," I replied.

    Five or six li further through a bamboo grove lay Yangjian Temple, with level ground enough to build upon. East of the temple, a thousand-fathom red cliff rose sheer. People had carved a slanting path through it. After another li, we crossed a small ridge and descended to Zhenshu's farmland. He urged us to stay, but evening approached and rain threatened floods. "Wang Ziyou reached Andao's gate but turned back without entering—why must I now enter your home after days of travel together?" He accepted gracefully, mentioning his foot ailment prevented him accompanying us fully.

    That evening we reached Sajin post station, where my legs ached too severely to walk further. The next day, I sent my companions back to Tianling and rode south, following the great river. Westward rose layered blue mountains—Duryu's outlying peaks. At noon we reached Shanyin County and ascended the Huanye Pavilion. Reading its inscription while gazing upon the clear river below, I felt the melancholy of time flowing past. I rested awhile, then mused: "To choose humane places to dwell shows wisdom; to avoid barren trees shows acumen. The county is named Shanyin, the pavilion Huanye—does not this evoke admiration for Huiji's mountains and waters? How might we here perpetuate the elegance of the Eastern Jin?"

    Southward from Shanyin, all landscapes were crystalline and lustrous—remnants of Duryu's essence. At Xinan post station, we forded a river and reached Dancheng. I half-jokingly called it Danqiu City, making it a place of immortals. The local magistrate Cui Jingfu provided generous provisions. In the flower courtyard stood a hundred black bamboos; I selected two sturdy ones for walking staves, sharing one with Baiyuan.

    West from Dancheng fifteen li through tortuous terrain lay a broad plain where clear water flowed westward. Following cliffs north for three or four li, we reached a valley mouth. At the entrance, carved characters read "Gate of Guangji Cliff." The script was archaic and strong—reputed to be by Cui Guyun's own hand. Five li further appeared thatched cottages and cooking smoke. We forded a stream and entered through persimmon trees. All the mountain's timber was chestnut. A grand sutras repository building stood encircled by walls. Beyond, up the western slope among trees, a temple bore the tablet: "Zhiyishan Duansu Temple."

    A stele before the gate recorded a great monk's inscription by the High Official Li Zhimao of Goryeo, built during the Dajing period of the Jin. The ancient Buddha hall had simple, austere construction. Wall paintings showed two figures with official regalia. The resident monks said "A Silla minister named Liu Chun renounced his position and founded this temple, naming it 'Severing the Mundane.' His image remains on a wooden record here."

    Walking through the halls, we passed a fifty-step corridor to reach an imposing ancient tower—its beams were rotted but still climbable. From the balcony, the courtyard below held several plum trees. "These are the political hall plums," they said. "Magistrate Qiang Wenjing's grandfather, Duke Tongjing, studied here in youth and planted one plum tree by his own hand. Later, upon achieving office as Minister of the Political Hall, he became famous. His descendants continue the custom." Exiting the north gate, crossing a ravine through overgrown brush, we found an ancient stele: "Inscription of Monk Shenxing" by Kim Heanjong, Vice-Minister of War in Silla, erected in the eighth year of Yuanhe of Tang. The stone was crude, scarcely a few feet taller than other inscriptions. The characters were illegible.

    Within the northern wall stood a meditation hall where the abbot dwelt. Mountain camellias surrounded it. East of the hall lay a deteriorated structure, reputed to be the Zhiyuan Hall. Below it stood a tall new structure capable of hoisting a five-zhang flag—the monks hoped to weave a thousand-Buddha tapestry within. Hundreds of temple buildings lay abandoned, their monks long departed. The east corridor held five hundred stone Buddhas, each of differing form and aspect, grotesque beyond description.

    Returning to the abbot's quarters, we examined old documents: three sheets of white mulberry paper, refined and supple, like modern official documents. One bore the signature "King Wang Jie"—the personal name of King Injong. Another: "Goryeo King Wang Hyeon"—that of King Uijong. These were morning inquiries to the Great Master. A third bore "Dade" and in one place "Huangtong Dade," the year-name of Mongol Emperor Chengzong, yet the dates did not align. "Huangtong" was the Jin's Emperor Taizong's year-name. How ironic that Injong and Uijong, adopting barbarian chronologies and devoutly supporting Buddhist priests, nevertheless suffered—Injong was tormented by Yi Jagyeom, Uijong barely escaped calamity at Geoje. Such is the futility of serving false gods!

    We found damaged emerald silk manuscripts in the style of Wang Xizhi—the brush strokes flew like startled geese, inimitable in grace. There were writings on yellow silk and purple silk, inferior to the emerald versions, all fragmentary. We also found an official appointment document bearing the combined seals of six ministries—half was missing, yet worth seeing for those who love antiquities.

    Baiyuan's feet were blistered; he dreaded further climbing, so we stayed a day. A monk named Gai was good company. At dusk, Magistrate Jingong sent two performers to entertain our mountain journey, and a tribute student named Kim Jungdon to attend our brushes and inkstones.

    At dawn, fine rain fell. We set forth with rain gear, the musicians playing pipes and flutes ahead, Monk Gai as our guide. Exiting the cave and looking back, water embraced the mountain, the settlement deep and secluded—truly a hermit's haunt. Pity it served the clergy rather than high scholars. West ten li across a great river—the lower Salcheon—we turned southwest, traveling twenty li through Duryu's foothills. The landscape was open, mountains gentle, clear streams and white stones delightful throughout. Turning east through ravines with clear water and sharp stones, then north again, we forded a stream nine times, then eastward over a wooden bridge beneath dense trees blocking the sky. The path climbed six or seven li until we encountered two ginkgo trees of enormous girth and height facing each other.

    Inside the gate lay an ancient inscription reading "Record of the Water-Land Spiritual Assembly of Five Terrace Mountain." Reading it, I found the writing excellent—composed by Goryeo Scholar Kwon Jeok during Zhao Song's Shaoxing era. The temple had grand towers and numerous buildings with hanging banners and streamers. It held an ancient Buddha cast by King Injong, it was said, along with his iron staff still preserved.

    As evening and rain approached, we stayed the night. At dawn, the monks gifted us straw sandals. Exiting northward, mountain rose on the right, valley on the left. For ten li we walked through trees on a perilous path. The cave mouth gradually widened with tillable plain beyond. Another ten li brought us to settlements—people shaped wood for tools, forged metal for livelihood. "Spring blooms into spring, autumn's leaves fade to autumn," I observed. "Such is the world." The accompanying monk replied, "This remote place has no oppressive magistrate; still, for generations the people have suffered heavy taxes and corvée."

    Five li further we reached Meogye Temple. Though reputed the finest sanctuary on Duryu, it somewhat disappointed initial expectations. The buildings were bright and beautiful, decorated with gold and silk, sewn into Buddha's robes—all admirable. The thirty resident monks maintained silence, practicing with the same diligence as those at Jintai. After brief rest, we took up our staves and entered a bamboo thicket, losing our way until reaching Zuofang Temple, where only three or four monks dwelt.

    Before the temple, chestnut trees had been felled by axes. "Why?" I asked. "Villagers wish to farm here; we cannot stop them," they replied. I sighed. "Even Taishan's long valleys face cultivation. Our nation's population grows daily. We must think how to enrich and educate them."

    We rested briefly, then summoned the musicians to dispel gloom. A ragged-robed monk danced in the courtyard with captivating grace. We ascended the front peak and sat upon a log spanning a vast gorge. As twilight deepened and pipe and flute harmonized, the mountains echoed, and our spirits soared. When the mood passed, we descended to a streamside stone and washed our feet.

    The day remained overcast; we lodged at Dongshangyuan Temple. At midnight, I awoke to stars and moon shining clear, cuckoos calling in confusion, my mind sharp and sleepless.

    My elder brother Kim Haengjon arrived, urging us to prepare for Cheonwang Peak the next day. At dawn, we bound our legs tightly and advanced through forest where roots and fallen timber tangled, brush obscured vision, sword bamboo grew thick, and shoots pierced the ground. We crushed them underfoot. Snakes lay across the path. Fallen timber of fine woods—nanmu, yuanzhang—lay scattered. Some we crawled beneath; others we climbed over. What a pity these materials, never meeting the carver's eye, were destined to fade in empty mountains! Yet perhaps they fulfilled their natural span.

    I walked ahead to a stream stone. Baiyuan struggled; a rope was tied around his waist, and a monk pulled him forward. "Where did the monk capture this prisoner?" I asked. Baiyuan laughed. "The mountain spirit merely arrests the vagrant creditor." He had visited these mountains before and answered playfully. Desperate with thirst, we all drank water mixed with grain flour.

    No path existed—only a thousand-fathom cliff's spray gathered into a stream cascading down like an inverted river of silver. Great stones tumbled atop each other, their mossy surfaces treacherous. Passing youths piled small stones to mark the way. Tree shade blocked all light. We labored upstream, pausing at every five or ten steps. When the stream ended, we entered bamboo again, where bare stone dominated. Grasping roots and vines, climbing with gasping breath for ten-plus li, we reached a peak crowned with azaleas. Delighting in this creation's abundance, I broke a single flower to wear; all attendants followed suit.

    Reaching a peak called Sejon Rock, its cliff was sheer yet possessed a ladder to climb. From its height, Cheonwang Peak seemed mere tens of li away. We pressed onward. The path descended; five li further brought us to Beopgye Temple with only one resident monk. Tree leaves grew thick, mountain flowers bloomed—late spring indeed. After brief rest, we continued upward. Stones resembled ships and gates. The path wound and twisted through caverns and crevices. Grasping stone edges and roots, we barely reached the summit as thick mist enveloped all—nothing visible beyond arm's length.

    The monastery cook arrived with a pot, finding a level place where stone-filtered water dripped into a spring. Too exhausted to climb further, we began preparing rice. The mountain offered no other wood except trees resembling fir and cypress that the monks called "brush wood." Cooking with it spoiled the rice's flavor. So the ancients understood that fuel matters!

    People say Duryu abounds in persimmons, chestnuts, and pine nuts—autumn winds make valleys overflow, feeding monks. This is false. When even other vegetation struggles, how could fruit thrive? Each year officials demand pine nuts; residents secretly purchase them from other regions to fulfill taxes.

    At dusk we reached the peak's top. A stone platform barely held one-room shed with a stone female figure inside—the "Heaven King." Paper money scattered on beams. Inscriptions read: "Sugseon Kim Jongzik, Gyeom, Goyang Yu Hooin, Geukgi, Hashan Jo Wi, Taiheo, together ascended Seonghu Imjin's mid-autumn day and further names." Viewing previous visitors' names, many were contemporary worthies. We slept in the shrine, wearing heavy quilts. Attendants kept fires burning outside against the cold.

    At midnight, heaven and earth cleared. The vast plain glowed white as clouds settled into valleys like tidal waters rising, white waves driving snow while exposed peaks stood as islands. Leaning against the stone wall, my spirit grew reverent. My body seemed poised above primordial chaos; my heart flowed with all existence.

    On the twenty-ninth day at dawn, I watched the sun rise from Yanggok. The clear sky gleamed like polished bronze. Surveying in all directions, ten thousand li opened to sight. All mountains became ants' mounds and earthworm hills—describable through Han Yu's poem on Nanshan, yet fulfilling Confucius's mountaintop ascent in spirit. Such feelings overwhelmed me, gazing down upon the dusty world.

    Duryu's southeast was ancient Silla; its northwest was Baekje. Countless insignificant creatures—like gnats in earthenware—appeared and vanished. How many heroes lay buried here? That we ascend unharmed today is surely heaven's gift. Yet amid peaceful prosperity's smoke and fires, myriad joys and sorrows, sorrows and joys, play out discordantly.

    I spoke to Baiyuan: "How might we join immortals like Wangquan, soaring beyond cranes, our bodies wandering beyond eight directions, our sight grasping one yuan's full measure, witnessing when the qi exhausts?" Baiyuan smiled. "Impossible." So we prepared offerings for the shrine.

    I composed this inscription:

    "Of old, sage kings established hierarchies. Only the Son of Heaven could sacrifice at Five Peaks and Four Rivers; princes sacrificed only within their fiefs. Lesser lords each had appointed duties. In later times, great mountains and rivers came to receive offerings from literati and travelers passing below.

    Duryu Mountain lies far in our maritime realm, spanning hundreds of li, bordering the two provinces, protecting dozens of states below. Surely great celestial spirits dwell there, raising clouds and rains, storing essences to bless the people infinitely.

    I and Scholar Jeong Yeochang, keepers of the right path, lifelong readers only of sage texts, destroyers of heterodox shrines we encounter, this summer planned mountain viewing. Upon reaching Duryu's slopes, mists and rain obscured its wonders. Yet yesterday's clouds parted, sun and moon brightened, and silent prayer to Hengshan's spirit—less generous than to Han Yu—

    Asking residents, they wrongly called the deity Mayadevi. But Zhanbi, our nation's great scholar of vast learning, consulting Li Seunghu's Record of Imperial Names, established the deity as Uisuk Queen, consort of our founding king, who unified Samhan and freed our people from conflict, whose shrine on great mountains eternally receives the people's offerings.

    I lost my father at weak-candle age. My aged mother remains. The western hills' light grows near. My love of each moment has never wavered. As Zhou Wen was nine when his son sought longevity, daring to make this mountain journey a prayer, daring to beseech for my mother's years. Simple rice, clear water—we value cleanliness and respect. May this be enjoyed."

    Written, I raised the cup. Baiyuan objected: "The world calls her Mayadevi. Your naming her Uisuk Queen may invite suspicion. Better to abandon both." I replied: "Setting aside Uisuk and Mayadevi, the mountain spirit can still receive the offering." Baiyuan said: "Did not the Master ask if Taishan is inferior to Lin Fang? Moreover, the state does not burn incense to mountain spirits but to the holy mother, or even Kasyapa. What then?" "Then Duryu's spirit receives nothing," I said. "Discarding the realm's guardian to promote false worship—that is the failure of those overseeing ritual." So we ceased.

    In life, I'd only known clouds adorning the sky, not that they float mid-air. Here they spread beneath us at noon's shadow-light. As afternoon approached, mist gathered. We descended through the Stone Gate to Xiangji Temple. The monks congratulated us: "Long dwelling here, this year many sought the upper peak but were blocked by wind, rain, and clouds. No one saw Duryu entire. Last night's omens suggested rain, yet we ascended and immediately cleared—remarkable!"

    Before the temple, a sheer cliff-face rose, called Gold Crag Peak. Gazing from it, countless strange peaks scattered before us, white clouds forever encircling them. From Beopgye through the upper peak to Xiangji, all involved circling layered cliffs where stone mushrooms covered mountainsides—layered stone everywhere. Fallen leaves clogged stone holes, plant roots took hold, branches grew bent and short, all bending southeast. The upper peak was worst. Azaleas had barely opened—just one or two flowers, buds unopened filling branches—truly early spring.

    The monks said mountain flowers and leaves flourish at fifth month, wither from sixth month onward. I asked Baiyuan: "The peak rises heavenward; shouldn't it receive yang first, yet delays instead?" Baiyuan replied: "Earth is eighty thousand li from heaven. We walked days to reach the upper peak, which is less than a hundred li from earth—who knows its distance from heaven? It does not receive the sun first but only the wind, being exposed and solitary."

    I observed: "All things' growth avoids the heights. Yet heights endure wind-rain's accumulation; lowlands suffer the axe's damage. What remains unharmed?" Stacked beside Xiangji Temple lay hundreds of pieces of timber. "What purpose?" I asked the monk. "This old one traveled Hunan provinces begging, transported these to Seomjin River over six years to rebuild our temple."

    I replied: "Our Confucian scholars lament their schools' declining state. Buddhism, originating in the western regions, captivates ignorant masses more than the Literary King. People's susceptibility to false teachings exceeds their faith in righteousness."

    From the temple, seeing the distant sea, I told the monk: "Between heaven and earth, water exceeds earth. Our mountains exceed plains; our population swells daily with nowhere to settle. You praise compassion—for all beings, couldn't you identify Duryu's source, dig from Changbai Mountain, fill the southern sea, create ten thousand li of fertile plain for human habitation, and produce karmic merit surpassing even Jingwei bird carrying stones?"

    "Undeserving of such words," he replied.

    I continued: "High banks become valleys; seas become mulberry fields. In cloudy mountains, in stone halls, cultivating golden pills, abandoning your nirvana's path, learning their longevity technique—when Duryu becomes a valley and the southern sea becomes a mulberry field, we shall together preserve our years. How is this?"

    "I wish to establish karma," he said. We clapped hands and laughed heartily.

    On the fourteenth day, at Lingxian Temple, we rested. Its structures were impressive—a singing Buddha platform before it, a sitting-high platform behind, rising a thousand fathoms. To the east, the Ling Stream poured through split bamboo. To the west, the Jade-Clear Water, where eagles drink, they said. To the north stood a Kasyapa stone image. Within the hall, Kasyapa's portrait was painted with an inscription—the "Unwearying Hall" three treasures. Smoke-stained and rain-damaged, I lamented these jewels abandoned in emptiness. Baiyuan said: "Better to preserve them publicly on famous mountains for connoisseurs to appreciate."

    People offered donations to Kasyapa and the Heaven King seeking blessings. We slept in the dharma hall. Thick mist and violent winds assailed the doors and windows—the foul air was unbearable, forcing us to depart early.

    On the fifteenth day, we traveled along the mountain ridge westward. North of the ridge lay Hamyang lands; south lay Jinju lands. A woodcutter's path divided them. After long wandering and observation, we continued through tree shade—all earthen mountains with discernible paths, unlike the previous treacherous routes. Descending suddenly from the peak, we reached Uishen Temple at noon, situated on level ground with residents' names inscribed on walls.

    Over thirty monks practiced diligently. Bamboo groves, persimmon orchards, and vegetable plots sustained them. I realized I'd returned to the human world. Yet turning to gaze at the blue mountains, I felt farewell's melancholy and apology to monkeys and cranes.

    The hall-supervisor Beophae was a capable monk. After brief rest, we departed, avoiding high climbs to wade along streams over white stones—the grotto was clear and deep, delightful. We paused to observe fish, and reached Sinhung Temple where clear pools and stones offered eternal leisure. The temple, built near a stream, surpassed others; visitors forgot to leave. As dusk approached, we entered; it was a dharma practice ground—bells and drums clamored, people crowded chaotically. I felt somewhat disappointed.

    That day we'd walked forty-odd li through treacherous mountain paths. The monks insisted we'd walked well. In my youth, watching postal runners and common soldiers walk, even pursuing horses seemed difficult. Early on the mountain journey seemed heavy-stepping, yet after days, my legs grew lighter, realizing all things depend on habit.

    I'd always used two staffs; only on the twenty-sixth day did I abandon them for horseback.

    Two monks, Yunzhong and Liaolong, escorted us to a small bridge. Liaolong said: "Recently a retired master lived at Sinhung Temple. One day he told his disciples a guest would come—prepare and wait. Soon someone arrived on a white colt, leading with grapevine reins, moving fast, walking the single log like flat ground. Everyone was amazed. He reached the temple; they welcomed him into a room. They spoke all night—no one could remember what about. Next morning he departed. A servant named Ji Kang, studying at the temple, suspected him unusual and held his bridle. The man brushed him away with his whip; his sleeve dropped a scroll. The servant grabbed it; the man said it was mistakenly shown to earthlings—treasure and keep it secretly, never reveal it to the world—and departed, crossing the bridge again. That Ji Kang is now white-haired, still living in Jinju, but shows his scroll to no one. That man was Cui Guyun, who didn't die but resides in Qinghe Grotto."

    Though the tale was wild, worth recording. Baiyuan and I tested the bridge; barely stepping forward, vertigo threatened. We returned and forded downstream instead.

    Exiting the valley, bamboo densely covered the hills; water flowed greenly. Villages gradually appeared. On the western mountain base stood ancient ruins—called old Hwagae. Traveling five li through tumbling stone streams eastward one li, two streams converged where twin boulders faced each other; carved characters read "Shuangxi Stone Gate." Compared to "Guangji Cliff Gate," these characters were larger but stylistically crude, like children learning to write. Beyond the gate one li lay an ancient stele with turtles and dragons; its inscription read "Shuangxi Temple Former Zen Master Zhenjian Stele," with a note: "Composed by Former Western Kingdom Superintendent, Chamberlain, Inner Court Official with Purple Goldfish Pendant, Minister Cui Zhiyuan, by imperial order," erected in Guangxi third year (Tang Emperor Xizong's reign). Nearly six hundred years had passed—ancient indeed.

    Human existence and political fortunes succeed each other endlessly, yet this mute stone stands alone, unchanged. What cause for reflection! I've seen many inscriptions. The Duansu and Shenxing steles date to Yuanhe, preceding Guangxi. The Five Terrace Water-Spirit Record by Kwon Jeok, a literary figure of that age. Yet only this inscription moves me endlessly—is it Guyun's hand-traces remaining, or does Guyun's spirit, wandering mountains and waters, resonate with one hundred generations hence?

    If I'd lived in Guyun's era, I'd have attended with staff and sandals, preventing him from walking alone seeking Buddhism's disciples. If Guyun lived today, he'd surely hold an important position, adorning the state with elegant prose, and I'd have the honor of assisting with brush and ink at his gate. Stroking the lichen-covered surface, I could not suppress sighs. Reading his words, they were ornate and beautiful—why compose for Buddhism? Perhaps he learned from late Tang without changing such habits? Or, remaining detached, watching this declining age, rising and falling with it, sheltering in Buddhism to hide himself? Impossible to know.

    North of the stele, a centuries-old scholar tree spread its roots across the stream—also Guyun's own planting. Temple monks, burning the garden, accidentally ignited it; after dragon-and-tiger reversal, the surviving trunk measured more than ten feet. Monks still tread its roots, calling it the Gold Bridge. Alas, plants possess life-essence and cannot match stone's longevity.

    The temple's north held ruins of Guyun's famous Eight Rhymes Pavilion. Monk Yikong hopes to gather materials to rebuild it. After sitting briefly with Yikong, suddenly we heard knocking. Inquiring, we learned officials were catching river fish; high water prevented netting, so they needed pepper-tree leaves to poison them and pressed monks for these. "Bring killing-devices to our temple?" the monks protested. I too frowned. The Five Terrace people already suffered magistrate oppression; now Shuangxi monks would supply fish-killing tools. Mountain peace was gone.

    The next day rain detained us. On the twenty-eighth day, we ascended Shuangxi's eastern side, grasping stone steps and clinging to dangerous bridges for two li until a spacious grotto appeared—level enough to farm. This is supposedly Qinghe Grotto. I wondered: how could I reach here while Li Meishou could not? Did Meishou forget, or does Qinghe Grotto not exist but only legend?

    Advancing tens of paces, gazing into a sheer ravine, crossing precarious bridges, a hermitage appeared called Furi Hermitage, perched impossibly on the cliff, no land before it, four mountains steeply surrounding it. The hermitage monk said: "Every sixth lunar month, creatures with jade bodies, red crowns, long legs gather on the Xiangluo peaks' pines, drink from the Crane Pool below, then depart. I've seen them many times—this is the blue crane." How to capture and companion with a zither? East of the hermitage, flying springs cascaded down a thousand fathoms into the Crane Pool—truly the finest realm. From Denggui to here, sixteen days elapsed. Countless peaks competed to display beauty; ten thousand streams converged in flow. Wonder and awe abounded, yet my heart settled most on Furi Hermitage alone.

    Hearing of the cranes, I suspected this was what Li Meishou sought, yet the ravine was too steep—only monkeys could traverse it. Wives, servants, even cattle had no place. Both Yangjian and Duansu became temples; Qinghe Grotto remained unfound. What to do?

    Baiyuan said: "Pine and bamboo are both beautiful, yet less so than this gentleman. Wind and moon are both clear, yet less so than moon-shadow at zenith. Mountain and water both please the benevolent and wise, yet less than the water about which the Master spoke—'Water, water, water!' Tomorrow we shall leave this Yueyang city and gaze upon the Great Lake's ripples."

    "Agreed," I said.
  footnotes:
    - This journey covers sixteen days of travel through Duryu Mountain (Jirisan), with multiple stops at Buddhist temples including Denggui, Jintai, Yangjian, Duansu, Beopgye, Xiangji, and others. The author's companions are the scholars Jeong Baiyeon (also Yeochang) and Lin Zhenshu.
    - The repeated theme of 'cinnabar' (丹砂) references the Daoist pursuit of immortality through alchemical elixirs, which the author uses as a metaphor for his own spiritual and scholarly pursuits.
    - The mysterious references to Cui Guyun (Cui Zhiyuan, 857-908), a famous Tang-period poet-administrator, suggest a legendary tradition of his immortality and continued presence in the mountains.
    - The author explicitly critiques both popular Buddhist superstitions and Daoist immortality cults while paradoxically appreciating the mountain's natural beauty and the historical artifacts he encounters.
    - The 'blue crane' of the title appears to represent an unattainable ideal—a creature of legend dwelling in the most inaccessible reaches of the mountain, symbolizing both natural wonder and human limitation.
    - Throughout this extended prose narrative in classical Chinese, the author employs detailed topographical descriptions alternating with philosophical and historical reflections, in the style of sophisticated travel literature of the Choseon period.
